class Solution {
    public int racecar(int target) {
        int speed = 1;
        int position = 0;
        while (position < target) {
            if (speed > 0) {
                position += speed;
                speed *= 2;
            } else {
                speed = Math.max(1, -speed);
            }
        }
        return position;
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log(target))
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

We use a while loop to iterate until the car reaches the target position. Inside the loop, we check the current speed and update the position accordingly. If the speed is positive, we increase the position and double the speed. If the speed is negative, we set the speed to 1 to prevent the car from going into negative positions. The time complexity is O(log(target)) because the loop runs log(target) times to reach the target position. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a constant amount of space for the position and speed variables. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs simple arithmetic operations and does not consume significant energy.

